text: A more accurate comparison would be the 512GB Oled model since it is much closer in price.  It's also kind of a shitshow to set up things if you aren't used to Linux (although you should really learn if you aren't).  TBH, I don't find neither that appealing RN. The Steam deck is theoretically made to run 7th gens games and below and 8th gen games at medium settings at 40 fps. I don't really see the appeal without a generational upgrade that patches those into high settings and 60 fps for 8th genband allows better interface for better enhancements in lower gens. Since otherwise you are just playing mostly indies and older game rereleases. And at that point I would just get a switch and and if you really want something like emulators mod it for similar features and the Nintendo first party output. Which is honestly a better sell than the Steam Deck atm. You don't even need to use emulators for most games, you can just buy digital rereleases and these often come with gyro support build it which is also on the deck but you have to set it up yourself through Steam imput.  Respect Switch 2, it's pretty much just a Switch 1 with massive performance boost. Which basically trumps the advantages in the Steam Deck use to have in the games they share and have proper 1440p and 4k support through DLSS upscaling.  However, the Switch 2 games are a joke, but with game key cards making non first party output even more pointless than it already was. And the first party output is too early to make up for it.   So rn, I would say Switch 1 or even 2 is a better deal than the Deck, but that's because of how rocky it's OS is in it's current state and how the hardware was getting closer but not fully there for what they were aiming for.  A Steam Deck 2 which Valve is waiting for a proper generational jump to commit to can deliver the performance I mentioned before would absolutely smoke the Switch 2. Finally having the power to deliver the experience they always promised and likely with an Oled model from the get go. text: This video, literally has me thinking and reflecting. About a game that I loved and grew up admiring its game ever since it step foot in existence. I have seen a few videos that have explained why the Isle is a terrible game. But even they combined cant match, the details Zenny has done. Which is very commendable, because a lot of what you have mentioned are topics that I have gone through but never took notice of it because I assumed that I am expected to find all this information out myself.  You have pointed out the flaws the game has, which can be fixed but seems like in the eyes of Dondi there is no flaw.   I do love this game, but heck. Those who play the Isle, really do reflect on the time you use on the game. I have 3998 hours in the Isle, that is nearly 167 days worth of playing a video game that doesn't save any hard progress you put, lots of players I know would disagree and wouldn't mind. I know some who have 5000+ hours in the game. It may not sound much, but that is actually a big portion of your life.  This video is an hour long, but it is 100% worth watching. I had no idea what I was doing, I had no one to provide me support on what you are suppose to do in this game. I still remember, but I spent 3 weeks worth of time playing the game until I naturally understood on what I needed to do. Makes me wonder about The Isle's future though, I do not even play Path of Titans mainly because it is difficult to even find, I do not know if I am looking in the wrong places. Doesn't matter, back to the Isle. What will happen to the Isle 2 years from now? I mean currently the Trike has been released, Rex and Allo are about to be released at the end of the month. Time will tell us indeed.  All the best for you Zenny 👏✨

video_title: The Isle - The Worst Game In Early Access (and I can prove it)
text: I brought the Isle recently, because Dinosaurs are cool and I wanted to play as a Dino and do Dino things. My first three attempts at life ended with me starving to death while trying to look for something to eat.   I spent pretty much all of my first two lives figuring out the controls and interfaces, while starving.  Third life, figure stuff out as my crea, finally find food and get stalking and hunting down aaaaaand instantly get blindsided by a herbivore player, a Paci, i think, considering it headbutted me to death.  All that took about 2 hoursish  My honest thoughts so far is that its a good idea of a game, and it have a great game in its heart but its buried deep under a mound of truly baffling decisions, like migration zones. And the map feels so cluttered, yet so empty. Which is such a contradictory feat that I am frankly impressed.  I also agree that the prevalence of small dinos that do nothing to the food chain, is a chain to the games longevity.  I feel they need to focus more on expanding their medium sized dino roster. But also give some love to carnivores as it is an up hill struggle for them (except the damn croc) maybe add an apex predator to the game, doesn't have to be a Rex, could be an Allosaurus or maybe give the spotlight to another lesser known Thropod. Something that would give the carnivorous the edge.  Also increase the server capacity, 100 is way too small for the size of map

text: I'm a new player (I started playing a little over a week ago), and while I appreciate and agree with a lot of what was said in this video, I also think it's somewhat subjective. You might be right about there being a lot of bad game design, but that doesn't mean the game is no longer fun.  I've been addicted to this game since I started playing it. I see other people in this comment section talking about how the "community is dead" and "there's rarely any other players around," but that hasn't been my experience at all. Perhaps that's because I joined a very populated and friendly community server. There's always hundreds of players online at any given time, and because it's so populated, I encounter other players constantly. Due to the high player count, the server owners had to disable the npc animals. Even so, due to a well-balanced diversity of dinos on this server (and large total population), there's still plenty of opportunities for carnivores to get food. The server owners also take steps to balance the distribution of dinos and their behavior so bad actors can't egregiously disadvantage other players.  I only play Hypsilophodon, and I've been able to reach full-grown (well, reaching full-grown as a hypsil is easy, tbf) and nest multiple times. It doesn't take long for other players to hatch from my eggs, either. The same goes for groups I've been in where other Hypsils are the ones nesting. For me, the nesting experience hasn't been miserable at all. If anything, I'm appreciative of its realism. Animals irl have to deal with the vulnerability of limited food and safety when nesting.  It might be that being a part of a good server has made my experience vastly different from other players. I actually attempted The Isle years ago and had a terrible time with it; with both the game and the community. The game didn't explain anything (which is still an issue today), and the community was so unfriendly and unwelcoming that no one was willing to teach me anything either. It was only after recently seeing The Isle videos pop up on my feed that I became interested again. And this time around, other players were kind enough to help me when I was struggling, which also made me more willing to put more effort into learning more about the game myself.  With all the flaws and bad development choices currently plaguing The Isle, it's still one of my favorite games at the moment.

text: So I recently started playing the isle after watching videos from YellowTones. I liked dino games but I never got into them much before. I found a community on PoT and it gave me the confidence to try the Isle: Evrima. I really like the Isle, the aesthetic of the game and UI, it's VERY different than PoT but I don't feel one is better than the other. It's honestly more of a point of preference and mood. Sometimes I wanna play path and pester people (positive and negeative) on my Rhamph and have a good time. (I even got my hubby to play with me, we had a great time!) And other times I want to play Isle: Evrima. I have a comfortable pvp server via Metta's Den and a pve server via Life Breaks Free. And even there I switch. It took me about 50 hours of nearly constantly dying and playing with nesting players, before I finally found a dino that works for me. I'm a Herra but not the usual kind. I'm a peaceful scavenger. I can't really do the combat. I'm visually impaired and the darker lighting in the game makes combat nearly impossible for me. But I do have fun snagging lil bites of food from other carnivores or especially fishing on my pve server. Keeping a dino alive is really a joy with how awful the AI has been recently >.< Especially as you can't seem to kill any of it as a baby.   BUT and to the reason for my comment. This video was very informative and I agree with your assessment. I want to be a youtuber but none of the content I could get was worth anything. It was just me rushing to find food and dying. Or accidently killing myself, like smashing a Ptera into a tree. Or falling off a cliff as a Maia, woops. It was frustrating and a fair let down and nesting can be hit or miss. I really love it but after we've grown up, everyone tends to log off or leave which is a bit disappointing.  My main complaint for the Isle is (AI of course) but mostly, I want to be able to have multiple dinos. I don't want to lose the perma-death. I love the thrill of that and I think that's too foundational of the game. But I tend to only play on one or two communities and nesting happens a ton on various dinos and that's one of my favorite experiences. I want to log off my Herra and go run around with Troodons for a bit. Or get in on a canni skin raptor pack. But when my kiddo is home and needy, I really would like to be able to switch back to my herra, scavange when he's content and be able to partially afk in a gorgeous thunderstorm while I talk to or help him with whatever is happening. I am also an avid writer and being able to focus on both like my brain demands is really good and I've gotten really happy. Most of the time I'm not even stealing from anyone. It's just an abandoned turtle in the forest along the coast. Or a chicken someone killed but could never find. I'm not intruding on anyone, or griefing. I get the lil terrifying interactions and feel good about being able to survive. (Not so much dying to random starvation for no reason, I really agree, I wish we had the old spiro map back, that looked amazing. Honestly half the reason herra is so damn useful is because I can scale over these intrusive mountains in between me and critical scarps.)  Overall though, it was great to get some background on the game and understand why some things the way they are. And I am kinda curious where human vs dino is gonna go.

Keeping a dino alive is really a joy with how awful the AI has been recently >.< Especially as you can't seem to kill any of it as a baby. BUT and to the reason for my comment. This video was very informative and I agree with your assessment. I want to be a youtuber but none of the content I could get was worth anything. It was just me rushing to find food and dying. Or accidently killing myself, like smashing a Ptera into a tree. Or falling off a cliff as a Maia, woops. It was frustrating and a fair let down and nesting can be hit or miss. I really love it but after we've grown up, everyone tends to log off or leave which is a bit disappointing. My main complaint for the Isle is (AI of course) but mostly, I want to be able to have multiple dinos. I don't want to lose the perma-death. I love the thrill of that and I think that's too foundational of the game. But I tend to only play on one or two communities and nesting happens a ton on various dinos and that's one of my favorite experiences. I want to log off my Herra and go run around with Troodons for a bit. Or get in on a canni skin raptor pack. But when my kiddo is home and needy, I really would like to be able to switch back to my herra, scavange when he's content and be able to partially afk in a gorgeous thunderstorm while I talk to or help him with whatever is happening. I am also an avid writer and being able to focus on both like my brain demands is really good and I've gotten really happy. Most of the time I'm not even stealing from anyone. It's just an abandoned turtle in the forest along the coast. Or a chicken someone killed but could never find. I'm not intruding on anyone, or griefing. I get the lil terrifying interactions and feel good about being able to survive. (Not so much dying to random starvation for no reason, I really agree, I wish we had the old spiro map back, that looked amazing. Honestly half the reason herra is so damn useful is because I can scale over these intrusive mountains in between me and critical scarps.) Overall though, it was great to get some background on the game and understand why some things the way they are. And I am kinda curious where human vs dino is gonna go.
